Jan 16 2008 	A Little Gem in a Sea of Tourist Schlock	The Tuscan Inn at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco is in such a great location for tourism, I'm surprised there isn't a much larger hotel here. After reading countless reviews of this property, I was confident we could have an enjoyable stay here and avoid any potential pitfalls - and we were not disappointed. I discovered a special rate at Travelzoo, which probably swayed me to try this hotel, and made my own reservation with Best Western. There was no problem in them honoring the special rate. If you are bothered by street noise then be sure to ask for a room with a courtyard view. The courtyard is tiny - but we could not detect any street noise in our room on the second floor looking over the courtyard. Currently (January 2008) they are remodeling some rooms on the upper floors, and there is considerable construction noise in some areas that started after 9:30 AM and stopped by 5:00 PM. It would be a good idea to ask for a room away from the construction for the least noise, if you are going to be in your room during the day or sleeping in late. Gregory, at check in, was quick and polite and helpful with our request for a courtyard room. The room is a bit on the small-side, but I think that is the standard in San Francisco with only a few exceptions. Our room was very clean and fresh-smelling. One window did open, which kept the room from getting stale. Drawer space was minimal, with only two small but deep drawers, and the closet was a little small. Clothes for two people for five days maxed out the tiny closet. There is a refrigerator in the room with is also the mini-bar, so there isn't a lot of room in there for take-out food, but is ample for medications, etc. If you plan to use the refrigerator, make sure to take a key to the mini bar, or it will be able to get into it. The room includes a ironing board and iron, although using it would make the room a bit cramped. There is a wall-mounted hair dryer in the bathroom. The restaurant in the hotel - Cafe Pescatore - does the breakfast run for room service, it was adequate but a little overpriced. Lunch and dinner room service is provided by North Beach Pizza, which deliveries many Italian specialties including pasta, entrees, salads, sandwiches and of course - pizza. However, there are countless restaurants of all sorts and price ranges within a 1-4 block walk of this hotel, there is little reason to order room service. We were very happy with the location of this hotel. Within two blocks (and not even uphill!) you could catch the Mason-Powell cable car, also many of the Muni Buses go by the hotel and the &quot;F Line&quot; historic streetcar is only one block away. Just a 3 block walk north and you are on the waterfront of Fisherman's Wharf. There are two grocery stores (Safeway and Trader Joe's) within 2 blocks of the hotel. One of the things we enjoyed most, was walking away from the touristy area of Fisherman's Wharf and onto the side streets to look for restaurants. There are many smaller places with very good food at very reasonable prices, all within walking distance. Each night when we returned to our room, it had been cleaned up very nicely and restocked. We made sure to tip the housekeeping staff each morning, perhaps that insured that they did an outstanding job every day. We felt we got a reasonable value for the $99 rate we received and assuming we could get a similar or better rate, we would stay here again.	
Jan 9 2008 	Warm cozy Inn :)	The chinese lady manager who checked us in was a little on the snobbish side. The room is a little small, not much space for walkin after putting 2 open luggages. Overall it was cozy, love the folded little wooden planks window. Our windows faced the interior part of the hotel, no noise disturbance at all. The free drinks held every evening are welcoming after a long day out.Location wise, it is very centralized, walkable distance to the fisherman's wharf as well as the cable cars at both Hyde and Powell Streets (that is if you were to visit Chinatown, unionsquare, etc). There is a bus going to Japantown just right opposite of the Inn.	
Jan 4 2008 	Great stay but room 127 noisy	We stayed at the Best Western Tuscan Inn between Chirstmas and New Years. We too had a bad experience with street noise in room 127. It seemed as if the windows were open as it was that loud. We requested a change to another room for the remainder of our stay and they were very helpful and immediately moved us to room 361 which was quiet and peaceful. I would definately stay there again and recommend it to others, but only if you reserve an off-street or courtyard room.We were able to get a great $99.00 per night rate through travelzoo.com and I did not felt we received a great value.	
Jan 4 2008 	Great Location!	My husband and I spent 2 nights at the Best Western Tuscan Inn. My husband called the day before to ask if we could check in early as we were due to arrive 3 hours before check-in time, which is 3 pm. They said it would not be a problem. We arrived at the San Francisco airport and took at taxi to the hotel. The cost for the taxi was approx. 40.00 plus tip. We decided to take a taxi as we wanted to get checked in fast because we were due to take the Alcatraz tour at 1:55 pm. When we arrived at the hotel there was no problem getting a room. She told us the only room ready was facing the court yard. This was fine as we knew we'd only be sleeping in our room so the view didn't matter. We were given room 421. The room was small but it was fine for sleeping. It was clean, although I did notice several spiders in the room. Just small ones though. The bed was very comfortable as were the pillows. There was internet access available through your TV. There was a keyboard provided. We did not use this service but thought it was nice that it was available if needed. The room also came equipped with an alarm clock radio. There were a few things that bothered me, after leaving a tip the first day the maid never bothered to refill our shampoos, conditioner, or soap, and removed the part bottles that we had not used. I had thankfully kept some from the hotel we stayed at in Toronto before departing. The other thing that bothered me was after returning to our room in the late evening our window was left wide open. It was freezing cold in the room and I don't think it warmed up even with the heat on until the next day. Now I know we were on the 4th floor, but still I don't think it was proper for the maid to leave our window open all day/evening. We did not eat at the hotel restaurant, we chose to eat at the IHOP around the corner for breakfast and it was good food and service, and they are open 24 hours. We chose to eat there both mornings. For dinner we ate at Pier 39 both times. Swiss Louis the first night. It was fantastic! The second night we ate at the Wipe Out grill, it was okay. The hotel is very central to everything and I would stay there again for its location. We felt very safe walking around at night and we did see some vagrants but not one of them bothered us. I was surprised at the amount of homeless people and beggars but none of them bothered or even asked for money. Most of them just held out cups or had signs or were street performers working for tips. We come from a small farming community of 6000 people so if it didn't bother us I don't think it should be a concern for others.There were excellent street performers which we found very entertaining. We especially enjoyed the guy who does spray paint art. We purchased one of his paintings for 10.00. What a bargain!! One word of advise is to pre book your tickets for the Alcatraz tour. Luckily I had read here on tripadvisor that the tickets sell out fast and usually days or weeks in advance and I had bought mine a month ahead. I booked my tickets online through their website. There were several people looking for tickets on the Saturday and the next available tour was Wed. morning at 9 am. Lots of disappointed people. You want to take the Hornblower Alcatraz tour at Pier 33, you get to visit Alcatraz and do a audio tour. It was fantastic. We also did the Aquarium under the bay. It was wonderful as well. If you have any other questions please feel free to msg me and I will do my best to answer your questions. Enjoy!	
